snippet.textDisplay:
In an interview with Rolling Stone, Kathleen Kennedy complained how, and I quote, "Every one of these movies is a particularly hard nut to crack. There's no source material. We don't have comic books. We don't have 800-page novels. We don't have anything other than passionate storytellers who get together and talk about what the next iteration might be."

You had over two decades' worth of comic books, novels and video games to pull from, you dumb, arrogant bitch. There was enough established lore that you could have put out adaptions for years without ever needing to come up with anything new. But nah, throwing all that in the trash and hiring mediocre writers to come up with a new story was clearly the better option. Or maybe the Force just wasn't "female" enough in those Expanded Universe stories.
snippet.textOriginal:
In an interview with Rolling Stone, Kathleen Kennedy complained how, and I quote, _"Every one of these movies is a particularly hard nut to crack. There's no source material. We don't have comic books. We don't have 800-page novels. We don't have anything other than passionate storytellers who get together and talk about what the next iteration might be."_ 

You had over two decades' worth of comic books, novels and video games to pull from, you dumb, arrogant bitch. There was enough established lore that you could have put out adaptions for *years* without ever needing to come up with anything new. But nah, throwing all that in the trash and hiring mediocre writers to come up with a new story was _clearly_ the better option. Or maybe the Force just wasn't "female" enough in those Expanded Universe stories.

Nah, I think Ep 9 was the best of the set.

Brisk pace, no wasted scenes, completed character arcs (even Hux got one), and they took several of Rian's ideas and themes and developed them to interesting conclusions - the best of which being that weird Force-Link-Telepathy thing.

The rest of the Trilogy was a mess of wasted potential, but after watching the film most of the reviews I've seen seem to come from reactionaries who gave up on the franchise after TLJ.

snippet.textDisplay: empire still easily the best. Literally the only reason why people are slamming the new films is because of its female lead and directions they've taken. I couldn't care less about people's opinions. Star Wars has ALWAYS had controversy. Even the beloved first film everyone didn't like because they thought it would flop. And even empire had controversy because of its darkness and cliffhanger ending. In my opinion, time will suit the sequel trilogy well. Over the years people will grow to like them as they have with the previous installments. I'm a simple guy. I like Star Wars. ALL OF THEM.
